<subSubSection pageId="66" pageNumber="462" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="66.[113,753,445,1013]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,259,445,469]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Description.</emphasis>
Carapace subquadrate, about 1.4 times as broad as long, dorsal surface smooth; regions indistinct, median U-shaped depression shallow; some granules present on dorsolateral margins, only scattered granules on posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[310,413,573,597]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[113,148,2061,2083]" captionTargetBox="[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetId="figure-234@64.[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 52. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax; D, chelae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354061/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 52A</figureCitation>
). Anterolateral margin arcuate; posterolateral corner with angled prominence over base of posterior pereopods (
<figureCitation box="[389,505,637,661]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[113,148,2061,2083]" captionTargetBox="[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetId="figure-234@64.[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 52. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax; D, chelae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354061/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Figs. 52A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[520,571,637,661]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">53A</figureCitation>
). Orbit distinct, transverse; eye small, slightly movable, cornea black, wider than tuberculate peduncle (
<figureCitation box="[401,498,701,725]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 53B</figureCitation>
). Pterygostomial region with row of oblique striae, oblique row of setae under row of striae, adjacent to Milne Edwards’ opening (
<figureCitation box="[639,740,765,789]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 53B</figureCitation>
). Third maxillipeds relatively broad, tuberculate, without gap between them (
<figureCitation box="[277,385,829,853]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[113,148,2061,2083]" captionTargetBox="[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetId="figure-234@64.[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 52. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax; D, chelae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354061/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Figs. 52B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[395,442,829,853]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">53E</figureCitation>
); ischium longer than merus, with rounded mesial margin; merus broader than long; carpus, propodus and dactylus cylindrical; dactylus longer than propodus, combined length of dactylus, propodus and carpus shorter than that of merus and ischium; exopod narrow, 0.4 width of ischium, flagellum well developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[113,753,1053,1845]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">
Chelipeds stout, unequal (
<figureCitation box="[389,489,1053,1077]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[113,148,2061,2083]" captionTargetBox="[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetId="figure-234@64.[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 52. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax; D, chelae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354061/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 52D</figureCitation>
). Major chela (
<figureCitation box="[648,744,1053,1077]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 53G</figureCitation>
) with slight gap when fingers closed; large teeth present at cutting edge of dactylus; dactylus with longitudinal groove on outer surface, tufts of setae on cutting edge proximally; inner surface near upper margin with longitudinal ridge; palm slightly wider than long, surface with sparse tubercles on outer surface, shallow longitudinal groove on outer surface of fixed finger; carpus without setae dorsally, row of tubercles and setae dorsomesially; merus short, few tubercles and fringe of setae dorsomesially. Minor chela (
<figureCitation box="[589,688,1341,1365]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 53H</figureCitation>
) with relatively wider gap between closed fingers; dactylus with longitudinal groove on outer surface; inner surface with longitudinal ridge near upper margin; outer surface of palm covered by large tubercles, carpus and merus unarmed, fringe of setae on each dorsomesial margin. P2–P4 short, stout (
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[113,148,2061,2083]" captionTargetBox="[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetId="figure-234@64.[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 52. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax; D, chelae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354061/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 52A</figureCitation>
); P3 longest; P2 most slender, dactylus upcurved, few tubercles on upper margin, fringe of short setae on upper and lower margins, slightly shorter than propodus, latter with row of tubercles on upper and lower margins distally accompanied by setae, carpus longer than propodus, tubercles on outer upper half, tufts of setae distally, merus about 1.7 times length of carpus, upper and lower margins with row of tubercles and tufts of short setae. P3 stouter, longer than P2; P4 (
<figureCitation box="[196,281,1789,1813]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 53I</figureCitation>
) stouter than P3; ornamentation and setation as on P2; merus of P4 2 times as long as broad.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[113,752,1885,2101]" lastBlockId="66.[813,1452,189,373]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">
Male thoracic sternum broad (
<figureCitation box="[441,549,1885,1909]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[113,148,2061,2083]" captionTargetBox="[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetId="figure-234@64.[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 52. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax; D, chelae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354061/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Figs. 52B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[561,642,1885,1909]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">53C, D</figureCitation>
), sternites 1 and 2 fused, separated from sternite 3 by distinct ridge; sternite 3 separated laterally from sternite 4, medially appear fused, sternites 4–7 well developed, separated by distinct sutures; thoracic sternal groove short, extends obliquely from sternoabdominal cavity, reaching middle of sternite 4 (
<figureCitation box="[121,230,2077,2101]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[113,148,2061,2083]" captionTargetBox="[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetId="figure-234@64.[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 52. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax; D, chelae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354061/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Figs. 52B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[243,293,2077,2101]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">53D</figureCitation>
); sternite 8 exposed, triangular, as long as abdominal somite 1; sternoabdominal cavity not reaching middle of sternite 4. Male abdomen relatively narrow (
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[113,148,2061,2083]" captionTargetBox="[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetId="figure-234@64.[113,1453,624,2030]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 52. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115). A, overall view of carapace, chelipeds and P2–P4; B, ventral view of cephalothorax; C, frontal view of cephalothorax; D, chelae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354061/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Figs. 52B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[872,917,253,277]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">53F</figureCitation>
); somites 1 and 2 free; somites 3–5 fused, lateral margin sinuous; somite 6 distinctly shorter than length of somites 3–5, lateral margin forming blunt triangular expansion medially; telson short, with rounded, setose margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[813,1451,413,725]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">
G1 (
<figureCitation box="[863,991,413,437]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 53J, K</figureCitation>
) bent subdistally, directed anterolaterally, distal part slightly tapered, tip rounded with several spines, mesial and lateral margin with sparse long setae, apices not concealed under abdomen, exposed on thoracic sternal groove, obscured by setae of telson. Female abdomen narrow (
<figureCitation box="[821,919,573,597]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[136,171,2003,2025]" captionTargetBox="[145,1468,233,1951]" captionTargetId="figure-7@65.[125,1481,214,1978]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 53. Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species. A–K, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115); L, paratype female (4.3 × 3.1 mm) (ZRC 2012.1034). A, carapace; B, anterior view of carapace; C, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing sternoabdominal cavity and thoracic sternal groove; D, thoracic sternites 1–5, showing thoracic sternal groove and telson; E, left third maxilliped; F, male abdomen and telson, G, major chela; H, minor chela; I, left P4; J, K, G1; L, female abdomen and telson. Setae on chelae not drawn. Scale bars = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5354063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5354063/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 53L</figureCitation>
), with somites 1–6 fused, somites 1–5 with very shallow, indiscernible sutures, suture visible between somite 5 and 6 but functionally fused; somite 6 distinctly shorter than somites 3–5, lateral margin expanded subproximally, telson almost as long as somite 6, distal margin rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[813,1452,765,853]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,897,765,789]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Colour.</emphasis>
In life, carapace yellow or light yellow, merus and carpus of chelipeds and P2–P4 yellow, propodus and dactylus white yellowish (
<figureCitation box="[1001,1089,829,853]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[136,171,1890,1912]" captionTargetBox="[136,1474,472,1864]" captionTargetId="figure-7@3.[136,1474,472,1864]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Colours in life. A, Mariaplax ourabay, new species, holotype male (7.6 × 5.4 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2114), Oura Bay, Okinawa Island, Japan; B, Mariaplax ourabay, new species, paratype female (9.2 × 7.0 mm) (ZRC 2012.1032), Oura Bay, Okinawa Island, Japan; C, Mariaplax narusei, new species, holotype male (9.6 × 5.8 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2112), Funaura Bay, Iriomote Island, Japan; D, Rayapinus maenosonoi, new species, holotype male (6.6 × 4.9 mm) (RUMF-ZC-2115) Sesoko, Okinawa, Japan; E, Hexaplax megalops Doflein, 1904, male, (13.5 × 9.0 mm) (MNHN-IU-2011-1026), west of New Hanover; F, Hexaplax aurantium, new species, paratype male (12.1 × 8.4 mm) (MNHN-IU-2011-1527), south of Lae, Gulf of Huon; G, Hexaplax saudade, new species, paratype male (16.9 × 9.8 mm) (ZRC 2013.1692), AURORA, 2007, station CP2658, Philippines; H, Hexaplax saudade, new species, male (15.9 × 11.1 mm) (ZRC 2008.1456), Su-Ao fish port, Ilan province, Taiwan." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5353949" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5353949/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="66" pageNumber="462" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="66.[813,1451,893,950]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,938,893,917]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after Tadafumi Maenosono who collected the 
<typeStatus box="[854,900,926,950]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">type</typeStatus>
specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="66" pageNumber="462" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="66.[813,1452,989,1173]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,926,989,1013]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Remarks.</emphasis>
As mentioned earlier, 
<taxonomicName authority="Rahayu &amp; Ng, 2014" authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[1190,1306,990,1013]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Rayapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="66" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis box="[1190,1306,990,1013]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Rayapinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1324,1446,990,1014]" pageId="66" pageNumber="462" rank="genus">new genus</taxonomicNameLabel>
, is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Manning &amp; Holthuis" authorityYear="1981" box="[956,1070,1022,1045]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="66" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[956,1070,1022,1045]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Hexapinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the extent of the male thoracic sternal groove. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[1075,1316,1054,1077]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Rayapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="66" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maenosonoi">
<emphasis box="[1075,1316,1054,1077]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Rayapinus maenosonoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily separated from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="De Haan" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[979,1171,1085,1109]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="66" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latipes">
<emphasis box="[979,1171,1085,1109]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">Hexapinus latipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rahayu &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2014" box="[1224,1338,1085,1109]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hexapodidae" genus="Hexapinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="66" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[1224,1338,1085,1109]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="462">H. simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having proportionately much shorter and stouter P2–P4 with a very short dactylus, and a G 
<quantity box="[1058,1094,1149,1173]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="66" pageNumber="462" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
which the distal part is expanded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
